snippet.textDisplay: Dr. Mike, when I was a young teen I developed these sort of hard bumps below my kneecaps, on both legs. I remember when they first developed, they were very sensitive and caused me pain. I remember visiting a doctor with my mother, but I cannot remember the explanation the doctor gave as to why it happened, or I didn't understand it at the time. I DO remember him saying that I needed to do daily leg stretching exercises for these growths. To describe them in the best detail that I can...Right under both kneecaps, a slight bulging growth, and they were/are pretty hard to the touch. Basically they feel like bone. I'm 32 now and still have them to this day, and I guess forever, although they do not cause me any discomfort today. I don't remember them being painful for too much longer after my doctor visit. Maybe a couple of months discomfort at most. What exactly is this? Thanks!

snippet.textDisplay:
"Gen Z is whiny"
Well you know what? It's hard not to be whiny when you're working 30 hours a week at 16 years old in addition to school just so you can hold on to the hope that maybe you'll be able to afford college without going into crippling debt. It's ironic that you made a video (that I agree with) about doctors dealing with criticism from people who don't understand the stress they're under when you just criticized, generalized and infantilized an entire generation even though you don't understand the stress they're under. I have friends that had to drop out of school just to work full time to try and get their families through another month because their parents can't work due to physical disabilities and medicare is so expensive. Baby boomers absolutely ruined the economy and now Gen Z and Millennials have to pay the price. Less and less people are able to afford educations, more and more people are falling below the poverty line, and there are literal 19 year olds living paycheck to paycheck just trying to scrape by for themselves and their families. You have a successful youtube channel, a stable job, and enough money that you're able to regularly donate to charities (which I do commend you for). You are speaking from a place of privilege. You don't have student loans, you're not living in poverty. You've always been an open minded person who's been able to extend your empathy to those struggling. Young people right now are struggling immensely and are under constant stress, so you know what? Yeah, maybe we're kind of whiny, but until you're in the same position, you don't get to just ignorantly label behavior and reactions to situations you aren't in, because you have no proof that you wouldn't be whiny in that situation too. You never found yourself getting irritable under the stress of med school? It's a psychological reaction to stress. Maybe think a little more about the way your words are affecting people next time you want to call an entire generation whiny. Maybe think about the cause for that "whininess". For someone who prides himself on being empathetic to emotional struggles, who constantly encourages viewers to communicate their struggles to their primary care physicians, you really dropped the ball on this one.
